As suggested in the hint, we start by drawing the vertical and
horizontal asymptotes. The vertical asymptotes are $x = 1$, $x = -1$ and
the horizontal asymptote is $y = 2$.

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=.5\textwidth]{ScienceMathExamResourcesCoursesMATH110April2012Question5ga.jpg}
\caption{ScienceMathExamResourcesCoursesMATH110April2012Question5ga.jpg}
\end{figure}

We know that the function increases to the left of $x = -1$, increases
again between -1 and 0, and then decreases from 0 to 1, and then again
after $x = 1$. Furthermore, the graph must go through the x-axis at the
point (0,0) but not anywhere else. This suggests the following picture:

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=.5\textwidth]{ScienceMathExamResourcesCoursesMATH110April2012Question5gc.jpg}
\caption{ScienceMathExamResourcesCoursesMATH110April2012Question5gc.jpg}
\end{figure}

Confirming that this picture matches the concavity found in part
\emph{$f$} (concave up outside of (-1,1), concave up inside (-1,1)), we we
arrive at the final sketch:

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=.5\textwidth]{ScienceMathExamResourcesCoursesMATH110April2012Question5gd.jpg}
\caption{ScienceMathExamResourcesCoursesMATH110April2012Question5gd.jpg}
\end{figure}
